{
  "doc_id": "2471",
  "text": "Finally, the cost of an ISFET-based system can be reduced substantially through the use of standard fabrication processes, such as the CMOS family of processes used for the majority of integrated circuit manufacturing lines. The most common method to create an ISFET in CMOS technology is to use the silicon nitride passivation layer common to most CMOS processes for chemical sensitivity. Compared to the other available insulator material in CMOS processes SiO , ISFETs manufactured with an Si N insulator are more sensitive due to the type of surface sites of the gate [CITATION_1] . Using silicon nitride in a standard CMOS process to make ISFETs, Bausells et al. achieved a sensitivity of 47 mV/pH [CITATION_2] . In order to circumvent the nonideality of the thickness of the chemically sensitive membrane inherent in a CMOS process, a contact window is often used to post-process (deposit) a membrane of desired thickness while eliminating additional photolithography steps and still maintaining the remaining devices (electronics) and structure in a standard CMOS fabrication scheme [CITATION_3] . An example of such a device has demonstrated a pH sensitivity of 58 mV/pH. Unfortunately, both of these devices require an external, large Ag/AgCl reference electrode which limits the benefits of CMOS miniaturization and integration. Attempts to reduce the size and integrate the Ag/AgCl reference electrode on chip by patterning silver during fabrication and converting them to Ag/AgCl in a post-process dip in a FeCl solution have limited the size and subsequent effectiveness of the reference electrode [CITATION_4] .",
